roid dehydrogenase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8542736172676086, "span": {"begin": 1244, "end": 1280}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3284"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Delta;5-&Delta;4-isomerase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9904163479804993, "span": {"begin": 1282, "end": 1308}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3283"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "3&beta;-HSD", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9935113787651062, "span": {"begin": 1310, "end": 1321}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1586"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "17&alpha;-hydroxylase/C17-20 lyase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9854755401611328, "span": {"begin": 1324, "end": 1358}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1586"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "P450c17", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9968786835670471, "span": {"begin": 1360, "end": 1367}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1586"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CYP17", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9935412406921387, "span": {"begin": 1369, "end": 1374}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:35343"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "17&beta;-hydroxysteroid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9993805289268494, "span": {"begin": 1381, "end": 1404}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3293"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "17&beta;-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase type III", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9344005584716797, "span": {"begin": 1381, "end": 1427}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3293"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "17HSD3", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9759958982467651, "span": {"begin": 1429, "end": 1435}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "genes", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.7960994839668274, "span": {"begin": 1504, "end": 1509}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002784"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cholesterol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999182403087616, "span": {"begin": 1535, "end": 1546}}, {"id": ["CL:0000178"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Leydig cell", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8727118968963623, "span": {"begin": 1600, "end": 1611}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013739"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "testosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9981375932693481, "span": {"begin": 1631, "end": 1643}}], "text": "Steroid hormones play a critical role in sexual development, homeostasis, stress-responses, carbohydrate metabolism, tumor growth, and reproduction. These hormones are primarily produced in specialized steroidogenic tissues and are synthesized from a common precursor, cholesterol. Mitochondria are a key control point for the regulation of steroid hormone biosynthesis. The first and rate-limiting step in steroidogenesis is the transfer of cholesterol from the outer mitochondrial membrane to the inner mitochondrial membrane, a process dependent on the action of StAR (Stocco, 2001) and the subsequent transport across the inner mitochondrial space into the steroidogenic pathway, which is executed by TSPO (Hauet et al., 2005). Testosterone production by Leydig cells is primarily under the control of luteinizing hormone (LH). Stimulation of the Leydig cells results in the activation of StAR transcription and translation, which facilitates the transfer of cholesterol into the mitochondrial matrix to cholesterol side-chain cleavage cytochrome P450 (P450scc, CYP11A), which converts cholesterol to pregnenolone. Pregnenolone diffuses to the smooth endoplasmic reticulum where it is further metabolized to testosterone via the actions of 3&beta;-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase &Delta;5-&Delta;4-isomerase (3&beta;-HSD), 17&alpha;-hydroxylase/C17-20 lyase (P450c17, CYP17), and 17&beta;-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase type III (17HSD3). For review see (Payne &amp; Hales, 2013). Decreased expression of genes that are responsible for cholesterol transport and steroidogenic enzyme activities in the Leydig cell leads to decreased testosterone production.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:31:55 +0000 2026"}